                #projects 
                    .project.media-box.flip
                        .content 
                            .blurb
                                h1 RiverBatJS (Beta)
                                p RiverBat is a #[span Proof-of-concept] web application that leverages the tools provided through #[span MapBox] to build a 100% in browser Geographic Information System. Visualization is handled with Mapbox's #[span mapbox.js] - an extended version of the fantastic open source mapping library #[span Leaflet]. Geoprocessing is handled by #[span TurfJS] - a (at times) client side spatial processing library also provided by Mapbox. For intactivity I used  #[span JQuery] and the geodata management is crudely manipulated in a singleton until it is offloaded into the Leaflet object. 

                                p The goal of this project was to demonstrate that an affordable (see: free) GIS solution could be widely distributed through a browser. The app is simple enough to allow for people around the world to answer basic spatial questions and share spatial data. 

                            .social
                                a(href="http://github.com/gregorydgarcia/riverbatjs" target="_blank"): i(class="fa fa-github")  
                                a(href="http://greg.js.com/projects/riverbat" target="_blank"): i(class="fa fa-picture-o")  
                                //a(href="https://twitter.com/gregorydgarcia" target="_blank"): i(class="fa fa-file-text-o")   


                        .media
                            a(href="/projects/riverbat"): img(src="img/riverbat.png" alt="River Bat")

                    .project.media-box
                        .content 
                            .blurb
                                h1 Beer Points 
                                p Beer Points is a fun #[span data visualization] of the top 100 beers of five common american styles as voted on by the Beer Advocate community.

                                p First I #[span scrapped] the beeradvocate site using #[span python] then converted the results into a #[span geojson object]. A few #[span leaflet] plugins latter and we had a pretty snazzy map. 

                                p Instead of hardcoding in the density by state, the values are #[span calculated on the fly using TurfJS]. I think spatially responsive websites will play a big part in the future.  

